Indigofera tinctoria

   [6889.jpg]
    Authority   L.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Fabales:Leguminosae
     Synonyms
   Common names indigo
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 6889

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A small shrub like, herbaceous plant reaching a
   height of 1-2 m with spreading or ascending branches, composed leaves,
   5 mm long flowers and straight or slightly curved pods, containing 7-12
   seed. USES A blue dye is produced form the leaves. The leaves also have
   medicinal properties. The plant is also grown as a cover crop and green
   manure. The leaves are rich in potash and palatable to cattle. GROWING
   PERIOD Perennial shrub. North of Equator seed are sown in October or
   April, and the crop ripen in June-July. COMMON NAMES Common indico,
   Indian indico, Tom jawa, Tarum alus, tarum kaju, Tagung-tagung, Tagum,
   Trom, Khaam. FURTHER INF Scientific synonym: I. sumatrana. Common
   indico is probably native of Malaysia, now it has a pantropical
   distribution. It can be grown from sea level up to 1600 m in elevation.
   Heavy or continuous rain or to much water may kill the plant. Excessive
   heat and hot winds may cause withering. Green matter yields may be
   10-13 t/ha and dye yields may be 1.6-5.4 t/ha.

   Sources
   SOURCES (I. tinctoria L.)
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 50 [USE]
   Duke J 1981 pp 99-101 318 [DRA, FER, LIMIT, RAIN, TEMP, PH]
   Westphal E 1989 pp 161-164 [USE, TEXT, FER, RAIN, DRA]
   Lemmens R 1991 pp 81-83 [USE, DRA, FER, LIG, TEMP, RAIN]

